NAME
       host - DNS lookup utility

SYNOPSIS
       host [-aCdilrsTwv] [-c class] [-N ndots] [-R number]
            [-t type] [-W wait] [-m flag] [-4] [-6] {name} [server]

DESCRIPTION
       host is a simple utility for performing DNS lookups. It is
       normally used to convert names to IP addresses and vice versa.
       When no arguments or options are given, host prints a short
       summary of its command line arguments and options.

       name is the domain name that is to be looked up. It can also
       be a dotted-decimal IPv4 address or a colon-delimited IPv6
       address, in which case host will by default perform a reverse
       lookup for that address. server is an optional argument which
       is either the name or IP address of the name server that host
       should query instead of the server or servers listed in
       /etc/resolv.conf.

OPTIONS
       -a     is equivalent to setting -v and asking host to make a
              query of type ANY.

       -C     When used in conjunction with the -t soa option, queries
              will be sent to the authoritative name servers for the
              specified zone. The SOA records that each name server
              has for the zone will be displayed (not supported on
              LikeOS).

       -c class
              Make a DNS query of class class. This can be used to
              lookup Hesiod or Chaosnet class resource records. The
              default class is IN (Internet).

       -d     Print verbose output. This is equivalent to the -v
              option.

       -i     Use the obsolete IP6.INT domain for reverse lookups of
              IPv6 addresses, rather than the current default IP6.ARPA.

       -l     List zone: The host command performs a zone transfer of
              zone name and prints out the NS, PTR and address records
              (A/AAAA). Not supported on LikeOS.

       -N ndots
              The number of dots that have to be in name for it to be
              considered absolute. The default value is that defined
              using the ndots statement in /etc/resolv.conf, or 1 if
              no ndots statement is present.

       -R number
              The number of UDP retries for a lookup. number indicates
              how many times host will repeat a query that does not
              get answered. The default number of retries is 1.

       -r     Make non-recursive queries. Setting this option clears
              the RD (recursion desired) bit in the query which host
              makes.

       -s     Tell host not to send the query to the next nameserver
              if any server responds with a SERVFAIL response.

       -T     By default, host uses UDP when making queries.
              The -T option makes it use a TCP connection when
              querying the name server.

       -t type
              Selects the query type. type can be any recognized
              query type: CNAME, NS, SOA, TXT, DNSKEY, AXFR, etc.
              When no query type is specified, host automatically
              selects an appropriate query type. By default, it looks
              for A, AAAA, and MX records.

       -v     Generate verbose output. This is equivalent to -d.
              Verbose output shows the full response message in
              dig-like format.

       -w     Wait forever: The query timeout is set to the maximum
              possible.

       -W wait
              Wait for wait seconds for the query to complete. If
              wait is less than one, the wait interval is set to one
              second. The default is 5.

       -m flag
              Set memory usage debugging: the flag can be record,
              usage, or trace.

       -4     Use IPv4 query transport only.

       -6     Use IPv6 query transport only (not supported on LikeOS).

EXAMPLES
       host example.com
              Look up the address of example.com.

       host -t MX example.com
              Look up MX records.

       host -t NS example.com
              Look up nameservers.

       host -a example.com
              Show all record types (verbose ANY).

       host 8.8.8.8
              Reverse lookup.

       host -v example.com
              Verbose output (dig-like format).

       host -t SOA example.com 8.8.8.8
              Query SOA using Google DNS.

       host -W 10 example.com
              Wait up to 10 seconds.

SEE ALSO
       dig(1), nslookup(1)

